  "prompt": "What is Drambuie and what could I substitute for it in a recipe?",
  "response": "Drambuie is a sweet, golden-colored liqueur from Scotland, made from a blend of aged Scotch whisky, honey, herbs, and spices. It has a rich, complex flavor profile that combines the smokiness of Scotch with the sweetness of honey and herbal notes.\n\nIf you need a substitute for Drambuie in a recipe, here are a few options depending on the flavors you want to replicate:\n\n1. **Benedictine + Honey**: Benedictine is a herbal liqueur with a similar complexity. Mix it with a bit of honey to approximate the sweetness and richness of Drambuie.\n\n2. **Scotch Whisky + Honey**: Since Drambuie is Scotch-based, you can mix a good-quality Scotch with honey. Add a touch of vanilla or a pinch of spices (like cinnamon or nutmeg) to mimic the herbal notes.\n\n3. **Irish Cream Liqueur (e.g., Baileys)**: While not the same flavor profile, Irish cream can provide a sweet, creamy substitute in some cocktails or desserts.\n\n4. **Amaretto**: Amaretto has a nutty sweetness that can work as a substitute in some recipes, though it lacks the herbal and smoky notes of Drambuie.\n\n5. **Grand Marnier or Cointreau**: These orange liqueurs can provide a sweet and citrusy alternative, though they won\u2019t replicate the Scotch or honey flavors.\n\nChoose a substitute based on the role Drambuie plays in the recipe\u2014whether it\u2019s for sweetness, herbal complexity, or the whiskey base.",
